{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BzmogHiLqwa7AJe7JdSdnL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Installation\n     2→\n     3→This document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→All installation methods require:\n     8→\n     9→- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n    10→- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n    11→- **`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`** — for agent steps using Claude Code\n    12→\n    13→## Build from Source\n    14→\n    15→Clone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n    16→\n    17→```\n    18→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    19→cd cloche\n    20→make install\n    21→```\n    22→\n    23→`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\n    24→builds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the binaries to\n    25→`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→make install PREFIX=/usr/local\n    29→```\n    30→\n    31→Make sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n    32→\n    33→```\n    34→export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n    35→```\n    36→\n    37→### Build Requirements\n    38→\n    39→- Go 1.25+\n    40→\n    41→## `go install`\n    42→\n    43→If you have Go installed, you can install the binaries directly:\n    44→\n    45→```\n    46→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\n    47→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n    48→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche-agent@latest\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→This places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n    52→\n    53→You still need to build the Docker image separately. Clone the repository and\n    54→run:\n    55→\n    56→```\n    57→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    58→cd cloche\n    59→make docker-build\n    60→```\n    61→\n    62→## Pre-built Release Binaries (Planned)\n    63→\n    64→> **Note:** Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n    65→> describes the planned installation method for when releases are published.\n    66→\n    67→Download pre-built binaries from the\n    68→[GitHub Releases](https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases) page. Each\n    69→release will include archives for common platforms (Linux amd64, Linux arm64,\n    70→macOS amd64, macOS arm64).\n    71→\n    72→```\n    73→# Example: Linux amd64\n    74→curl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    75→tar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    76→sudo install cloche cloched cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/\n    77→```\n    78→\n    79→You still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n    80→`make docker-build`:\n    81→\n    82→```\n    83→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    84→cd cloche\n    85→make docker-build\n    86→```\n    87→\n    88→## Homebrew (macOS / Linux) (Planned)\n    89→\n    90→> **Note:** A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n    91→> planned installation method.\n    92→\n    93→```\n    94→brew tap cloche-dev/tap\n    95→brew install cloche\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→This will install all three binaries. You will still need the Docker image —\n    99→the formula will print post-install instructions for building or pulling it.\n   100→\n   101→## Docker-Only Usage (Planned)\n   102→\n   103→> **Note:** A dedicated `Dockerfile.daemon` for running the daemon in Docker\n   104→> does not exist yet. This section describes a planned future option.\n   105→\n   106→Running the Cloche daemon inside Docker would avoid any host installation\n   107→beyond Docker itself. This would be useful for CI environments or trying Cloche\n   108→without installing Go.\n   109→\n   110→Once available, usage would look like:\n   111→\n   112→```\n   113→docker run -d \\\n   114→  --name cloched \\\n   115→  -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \\\n   116→  -v /tmp/cloche.sock:/tmp/cloche.sock \\\n   117→  -e ANTHROPIC_API_KEY \\\n   118→  cloche-daemon\n   119→```\n   120→\n   121→Docker-in-Docker requires mounting the Docker socket. The CLI (`cloche`)\n   122→still needs to be available on the host (or in the same container) to\n   123→communicate with the daemon over the Unix socket.\n   124→\n   125→## Verifying the Installation\n   126→\n   127→After installing, verify that everything works:\n   128→\n   129→```\n   130→# Check the binaries\n   131→cloche --help\n   132→cloched --help\n   133→\n   134→# Start the daemon (if not already running)\n   135→cloched &\n   136→\n   137→# Build the agent image\n   138→make docker-build\n   139→\n   140→# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\n   141→cloche list\n   142→```\n   143→\n   144→## Upgrading\n   145→\n   146→To upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\n   147→If you built from source:\n   148→\n   149→```\n   150→cd cloche\n   151→git pull\n   152→make install\n   153→```\n   154→\n   155→The `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\n   156→and restarts the daemon automatically.\n   157→\n   158→## Next Steps\n   159→\n   160→- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n   161→- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n   162→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01TqxPW4GxLg6zT7F34LJEMm","session_id":"b222aa3d-4bbf-440c-993c-c83ddd6bf5b6","uuid":"485def00-1f1f-41ce-b94b-046a00c15579"}
